    "name": "Question 7 @ 2021/2022",
    "Question": {
      "content": "Electrical conductors are materials",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "that do not allow charges to flow freely",
        "that allow charges to flow freely",
        "that do not have charges",
        "that are insulators"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "that allow charges to flow freely"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "Electrical conductors are defined as materials that allow charges (electrons) to flow freely due to the presence of free electrons, which is why that allow charges to flow freely is the correct answer. Examples include metals like copper. That do not allow charges to flow freely describes insulators, not conductors. That do not have charges is incorrect because conductors have charges (electrons) that can move. That are insulators is the opposite of conductors. Thus, the correct definition is that allow charges to flow freely."
    },
    "topic": [
      "Conductors",
      "Electric Current",
      "Charge Flow"
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 31 @ 2021/2022",
    "Question": {
      "content": "If the current carried by lightning discharge is 20kA. Calculate the quantity of charges released to the earth during a 3.0seconds discharge.",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "2x10⁶C",
        "5x10⁶C",
        "2x10⁴C",
        "6x10⁴C"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "6x10⁴C"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "The quantity of charge is given by \\( Q = I t \\), where \\( I = 20 \\text{kA} = 20 \\times 10^3 \\text{A} \\) and \\( t = 3.0 \\text{s} \\). So, \\( Q = 20 \\times 10^3 \\times 3.0 = 60 \\times 10^3 = 6 \\times 10^4 \\text{C} \\). This makes 6x10⁴C the correct answer. 2x10⁴C and 6x10⁵C do not match this calculation."
    },
    "topic": [
      "Electricity & Magnetism",
      "Electric Current",
      "Charge Flow",
      "Units of Measurement"
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 35 @ 2021/2022",
    "Question": {
      "content": "The vector quantity that describes the flow of charges through any given area is",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "current density",
        "drift velocity",
        "velocity",
        "charge"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "current density"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "The vector quantity that describes the flow of charges through a given area is the current density, which is why current density is the correct answer. Current density \\( \\vec{J} \\) is defined as \\( \\vec{J} = \\frac{I}{A} \\hat{n} \\), where \\( I \\) is the current, \\( A \\) is the area, and \\( \\hat{n} \\) is the direction of current flow, making it a vector. Drift velocity is the average velocity of charge carriers (a vector but not the flow per area). Velocity is a general term, not specific to charge flow. Charge is a scalar quantity."
    },
    "topic": [
      "Electricity & Magnetism",
      "Electric Current",
      "Charge Flow",
      "Current Density"
    ]
  }
